SIMPLE: remnant
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Remnant
<hw>Rem"nant</hw> <pr>(r?m"n<it>a</it>nt)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>remanant</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>remanoir</ets>,
<ets>remaindre</ets>. See <er>Remanent</er>, <er>Remain</er>.]</ety>
<def>Remaining; yet left.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Because of the
<xex>remnant</xex> dregs of his disease.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Fuller.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And quiet dedicate her <qex>remnant</qex> life⟦br⟧
To the just duties of an humble wife.</q> <rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Remnant</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Remnant
<hw>Rem"nant</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>remanant</ets>. See
<er>Remnant</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>That which remains after a part is removed,
destroyed, used up, performed, etc.; residue.</def>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>remnant</qex> that are left of the captivity.</q>
<rj><qau>Neh. i. 3.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>remnant</qex> of my tale is of a length⟦br⟧
To tire your patience.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A small portion; a slight trace; a fragment; a
little bit; a scrap.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Some odd quirks and <qex>remnants</qex> of wit.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Com.)</fld> <def>An unsold end of piece goods, as
cloth, ribbons, carpets, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Residue; rest; remains; remainder.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Remodel</ent>⟦br⟧
